From a more fundamental perspective, a good movie is a choice of referent for a set of interesting ideas. But because the movie medium is so rich, it is always an incredibly redundant referent. My claim is that people (act like they) don’t realise *how* redundant it is. It's true that sometimes precision will be needed in factors like acting, visuals, dialogue, etc., in order to make the reference successful, e.g. there’s a subtle emotion that the actor needs to convey in his expression. And it's useful that we have access to those factors by courtesy of the medium. But a lot of the time the factors can vary quite significantly without compromising the reference at all.

Anyway that's my piece.
